  1. Do sales prices change over time? (Don’t test significances) Provide a graphic that supports your statement.
    • According to the graphic below, sales prices may change over time. The boxplots indicate that 2009 had the highest median sale price, and the red dots indicating mean sales price support this notion. However, the maximum sales price appears to decrease with time. The opposite could be said about the minimum sales price: it increased with time. However, the differences described above are subtle.
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(housing, aes(x = YearSold, y = SalePrice)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(group = YearSold)) +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", colour = "red") +
  theme_bw()

  1. What is the relationship between sales prices and the size of the house (living area)? Make a chart and describe the relationship.
    • The relationship between sales prices and the size of the house is a strong, positive, linear relationship. More variation in sales price occurs as living area gets large.
ggplot(housing, aes(x = LivingArea, y = SalePrice)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw()

  1. Use dplyr functions to:
  • introduce a variable consisting of price per square foot,
  • find the average price per square foot in each of the Ames neighborhoods, - exclude averages that are based on fewer than 10 records,
  • reorder the remaining neighborhoods according to the mean sales prices.
library(dplyr)
housing %>%
  mutate(price_per_sqft = SalePrice / LivingArea) %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(mean_price_per_sqft = mean(price_per_sqft),
            ct = n(),
            mean_sales_price = mean(SalePrice)) %>%
  filter(ct >= 10) %>%
  arrange(mean_sales_price) %>%
  select(-ct, -mean_sales_price)

  1. Draw a chart of the average sale prices by neighborhood and comment on it. Only consider neighborhoods with at least 10 sales.
    Extra challenge (0.5 point extra credit): write the code for this question and the previous one in a single statement.
    • Mean sales prices range from $94,000 to $310,000, with NridgHt and NoRidge having mean sales prices over $300,000. It appears that approximately 50% of neighborhoods have mean sales prices below $150,000.
housing %>%
  mutate(price_per_sqft = SalePrice / LivingArea) %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(mean_price_per_sqft = mean(price_per_sqft),
            ct = n(),
            mean_sales_price = mean(SalePrice)) %>%
  filter(ct >= 10) %>%
  arrange(mean_sales_price) %>%
  mutate(Neighborhood = factor(Neighborhood, levels = Neighborhood)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Neighborhood, y = mean_sales_price)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  coord_flip()

  1. Use dplyr functions to:
  • introduce a logical variable called ‘garage’ that is FALSE if the garage area is zero, and TRUE otherwise,
  • exclude all sales of houses that do not have a garage,
  • only consider 1 and 2 story houses (HouseStyle),
  • create a new variable YBCut from YearBuilt that introduces age categories that groups the year a house was built into intervals: 1800-1850, 1850-1900, 1950-2000, 2000+ (see ?cut).
house1 <- housing %>%
  mutate(garage = ifelse(GarageArea == 0, FALSE, TRUE)) %>%
  filter(garage == TRUE) %>%
  filter(HouseStyle == "1-Story" | HouseStyle == "2-Story") %>%
  mutate(YBCut = cut(YearBuilt, c(1800, 1850, 1900, 1950, 2000, 2010), 
                     labels = c("1800-1850", "1850-1900", "1900-1950", "1950-2000", "2000+")))
  1. Draw a chart of the previous data set. Draw side-by-side boxplots of the garage area by YBCut. Facet by the style of house. Describe and summarise the chart.
    Extra challenge (0.5 point extra credit): write the code for this question and the previous one in a single statement.
    • The chart below has two panes: the pane on the left is for 1-story houses and the pane on the right is for 2-story houses. In each pane there are side-by-side boxplots showing garage area by year. Year is grouped into 4 intervals (on the chart): 1850-1900, 1900-1950, 1950-2000, and 2000+. For one story houses, median garage size appears to be lower for 1900-1950 than 1850-1900, but increases from 1900 on. The same story can be told for 2-story houses. Median garage size is smaller for 1-story houses built in 1850-2000 than it is for 2-story houses. However, median garage size is larger for 1-story houses built after 2000. There appears to be more extreme outliers in the pane for 2-story houses than that for 1-story houses.
housing %>%
  mutate(garage = ifelse(GarageArea == 0, FALSE, TRUE)) %>%
  filter(garage == TRUE) %>%
  filter(HouseStyle == "1-Story" | HouseStyle == "2-Story") %>%
  mutate(YBCut = cut(YearBuilt, c(1800, 1850, 1900, 1950, 2000, 2010), 
                     labels = c("1800-1850", "1850-1900", "1900-1950", "1950-2000", "2000+"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = YBCut, y = GarageArea)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ HouseStyle) +
  theme_bw()
